Key signing party at the London Office
Key signing party at the London Office
A key signing party is an event at which people present their public keys to others in person, who, if they are confident the key actually belongs to the person who claims it, digitally sign the certificate containing that public key and the person's name, etc. It's very popular in Europe and will happen this time both in Paris and in London. Ludovic Hirlimann is organising it for Mozilla.
- London - City of Westminster - United Kingdom
Owner
Jean Yves Perrier

Key signing party at the Paris Office
Key signing party at the Paris Office
A key signing party is an event at which people present their public keys to others in person, who, if they are confident the key actually belongs to the person who claims it, digitally sign the certificate containing that public key and the person's name, etc. It's very popular in Europe and will happen this time both in Paris and in London. Ludovic Hirlimann is organizing it for Mozilla.

DebianDay 2014 Barquisimeto
DebianDay 2014 Barquisimeto
The Debian Day, which is celebrated every August 16, commemorates the birth anniversary of the Debian Project (in English, Debian Project), which is responsible for the creation and maintenance of Debian GNU / Linux distribution organization focused on GNU / Linux and GNU utilities. Founded in 1993 by Ian Murdock, the project has grown from a small group of hackers to what is now a worldwide community dedicated to the maintenance and development of this operating system group.

Software Freedom Day 2014 (Nepal)

Software Freedom Day
Software Freedom Day
SFD is a worldwide celebration of FOSS. Our goal in this celebration is to educate the worldwide public about the benefits of using high quality FOSS in education, in government, at home, and in business -- in short, everywhere! The non-profit organization Software Freedom International coordinates SFD at a global level, providing support, giveaways and a point of collaboration, but volunteer teams around the world organize the local SFD events to impact their own communities.

Code Rush (Documentary) Screening
Code Rush (Documentary) Screening
Code Rush is a 2000 documentary following the lives of a group of Netscape engineers in Silicon Valley. It covers Netscape's last year as an independent company, from their announcement of the Mozilla open source project until their acquisition by AOL. It particularly focuses on the last minute rush to make the Mozilla source code ready for release by the deadline of March 31, 1998, and the impact on the engineers' lives and families as they attempt to save the company from ruin.

Million Mask March - Zurich
Million Mask March - Zurich
Currently there is a discussion in Swiss parliament to reform the current law regarding digital law enforcement. In privacy-concerned circles this reform is seen as a massive decrement of privacy of Swiss people. One of the means to increase the enforcement would be a trojan horse-like tool which would be installed on people's computers. Therefore there will be a demonstration in Zurich to get us heard and get as many attention to the topic as possible, so not only geeks see the problem.

Become a Community Coordinator in Your Region!

The Mozilla Reps program is open to all Mozillians who are 18 years of age and above. Before you become a Mozilla Rep, you must follow our learning process so that you can become a good Community Coordinator in your region.

Community Coordinators are not a power structure over other Mozillians, instead they are here to help, empower and motivate other Mozillians to contribute to Mozilla projects.

There are tons of opportunities you can benefit from joining this program:

  • Access to a global community which includes people from many different countries and cultural backgrounds.
  • Direct support from Mozilla to help you empower others in your region to advance Mozillas goals.
  • Opportunity to help your local community grow.
  • Grow your leadership and communication skills and build networks with new people from many different countries around the globe.
  • Amplify Mozillas impact in your local region and functional area.

If you want to learn more about our program, you might want to connect with one of our currently active Mozilla Reps in your region, so you can learn and understand the challenges and opportunities of this program.

Find Mozilla Reps from your region

Major requirements:

  • The applicant needs to be at least 18 years old
  • The applicant needs to be active within Mozilla for at least 6 months

If you want to learn more about the Reps Program Selection Criteria please check here.

The Mozilla Reps application process involves two simple steps. Ready? Let's get started!

Thanks for your interest in making the Web better with Mozilla!
